1 Sec. 1. Department of Health and Human Services development of models
2 for expanded access to dental services. Resolved: That, based on the
3 recommendation of the Commission to Expand Access to Oral Health Care by Studying
4 Alternative Pathways for Obtaining a License to Practice Dentistry pursuant to Resolve
5 2025, chapter 107, the Department of Health and Human Services shall:
6 1. Consider the development of a so-called hub-and-spoke model to expand access to
7 dental services throughout the State. In developing the model, the department must include
8 as components of the model the dental services provided by the University of New England
9 and federally qualified health centers, mobile units and nontraditional dental care practices,
10 such as dental care practices that are limited in scope, that provide services in areas where
11 the population density is insufficient to support a dental provider setting up a practice; and
12 2. Explore options to establish dental specialist residency programs in the State,
13 especially for pediatric dentists, oral surgeons and orthodontists.
14 Sec. 2. Stakeholder participation. Resolved: That the Department of Health
15 and Human Services shall invite the participation of stakeholders to ensure the department
16 has the information and expertise necessary to complete the tasks identified in section 1,
17 including, but not limited to, representatives from the University of New England College
18 of Dental Medicine, the Maine Public Health Association, the Board of Dental Practice,
19 the Maine Dental Association and the Maine Dental Hygienists' Association.
20 Sec. 3. Report. Resolved: That, no later than February 15, 2027, the Department
21 of Health and Human Services shall submit a report that includes its findings and
22 recommendations under this resolve, including suggested legislation, to the joint standing
23 committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over health coverage, insurance and
24 financial services matters and the joint standing committee of the Legislature having
25 jurisdiction over health and human services matters. Each joint standing committee may
26 report out legislation to the 133rd Legislature in 2027 based on the report.
